<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cassiope</i> <i>mertensiana</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the dwarf shrub and herbaceous layers with <i>Antennaria</i> <i>media</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>nigricans</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>spectabilis</i>, <i>Kalmia</i> <i>microphylla</i>, <i>Luetkea</i> <i>pectinata</i>, <i>Oreostemma</i> <i>alpigenum</i>, <i>Phyllodoce</i> <i>empetriformis</i>, <i>Saxifraga</i> <i>aprica</i>, <i>Sibbaldia</i> <i>procumbens</i>, <i>Trisetum</i> <i>spicatum</i> and <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>cespitosum</i>. </div>
</div>

		
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 1 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is open to continuous and herb rich. </div>
</div>

		
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Subalpine to alpine slopes and basins with late-lying snow and subirrigation from surrounding slopes. Soils are well drained, acidic, and nutrient poor, often with organic matter accumulations. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Cassiope mertensiana</i> as a FACU* plant. </div>
</div>

		
