<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cassiope mertensiana </i>is a dwarf, rhizomatous shrub that grows to 50 cm tall. The evergreen leaves are scalelike. The flowers are white bells. Its decumbent stems root when they contact the soil. This species is common in the Cascades and northern Rocky Mountains (Hickman 1993). <br/>
<br/>
NatureServe (2007a) describes the <i>Cassiope mertensiana </i>dwarf shrubland alliance in the Pacific Northwest from California to Washington and Idaho, where <i>C. mertensiana </i>and <i>Phyllodoce empetriformis </i>are part of a subalpine parkland mosaic at timberline in the Cascades (Douglas and Bliss 1977, Franklin and Dyrness 1973). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cassiope mertensiana</i> grows in California at alpine and subalpine elevations in the Klamath Mountains (M261A), Southern Cascades (M261D), and northern Sierra Nevada (M261E) (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Although stands appear sufficiently large to warrant alliance status from our observations, we need to sample them in the Marble Mountains and Trinity Alps, on Mount Shasta, and in the Sierra Nevada for a definitive disposition. </div>
</div>

	

    
